WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.000
We're on.

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Today is Thursday, March 14, 2013.

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:24.000
My name is John Dittmer, and I'm here in Pickens, Mississippi with videographer John Bishop to interview Mr. Robert Clark,

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:30.000
the first African American to be elected to the Mississippi House of Representatives in the 20th century.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:38.000
This interview will become part of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington, D.C.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Representative Clark, we're delighted to be here today, and we thank you for taking the time to talk with us.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
It's a pleasure to have both of you here today.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:55.000
I usually begin the interview by asking the participants to talk about their family, and I'll do that.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:02.000
But I'm going to start this one by asking you to talk about this house that we're in now.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
I was born in this house.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:16.000
My father built this house approximately a hundred years ago, and this is the only address that I have ever had.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.000
I've never left this place.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Tell us about the history of the house and the family.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Well, my great-grandparents were slaves on the same property that we own today.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:44.000
And after slavery, my great-grandfather's former slave master sold him the property.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
And it has been in the family ever since.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:58.000
And when I was growing up, I felt like I wanted to go to Chicago, like everybody else was doing.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:13.000
I leave Mississippi, but after I graduated from Twest grade, my father, who was living here then, and my mother had deceased, and my older aunt.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:19.000
My father said, me and sister Annie want to see you.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Well, I got really afraid. I didn't know what they wanted.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
So finally, I made my mind up.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:33.000
I said, Dad, let's go over home and see what your sister wants.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:38.000
And I drove my boat regular car over there, and we got to the gate.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:46.000
I thought I was afraid before, but I really was nervous and we're shaking.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
So when I walked in, she was standing over the stone.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:03:00.000
Now, I really thought some girl had told a story on me and had said I had impregnated her.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.000
Well, I knew that wasn't true.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:18.000
So my father said, Sister Annie, here's this boy, here's, she said, boy, when you go to school and finish, we want you to come back home and take you to the family of Providence.

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:20.000
Oh, no, not me.

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:23.000
You know, I don't like the country.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.000
You know, I can't stand the field.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:34.000
I put up a strong argument, but my father and my aunt never said a word.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:44.000
So finally, when I had the argument all I could, I said, I don't want to, but if you all want me to, I will.

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
And she said, we do.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:04:02.000
And that's how I wound up coming back home and being on this place where, as I said earlier, my great-grandpa was slaves right on this plantation.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
This is the plantation where they were slaves.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Did you have brothers and sisters?

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:18.000
Yes, I had one brother and one sister by my father's first marriage.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:27.000
Then after my mother died, my father married again, and he had another son.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:35.000
But my sister, you know, saw Fetch to go to big sit in bright light.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:38.000
She went to California.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Then Chicago, and she followed while I'm up, and she's still living in Las Vegas now.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:46.000
Oh, wow.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:52.000
But my brother left home to go to school in Memphis, high school.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
Because we had no high school for African Americans then.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:06.000
High schools was only in the little towns, do right, Alexa, but you had to board to go to school there.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:21.000
So after my brother went to Yazoo City School for ninth grade, staying with the aunt of ours, he decided to go to Memphis and stay with our uncle of ours.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.000
And go to high school at Booker T. Washington.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.000
So he did, and he never came back home.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:29.000
So you were the one.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Yes.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:33.000
Well, I'm going to read you something.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:42.000
A quote, Jack Bass in his Gordwood to Melanie Nielsen's book about your campaigns for Congress begins with this sentence.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:50.000
As an 11-year-old Black youth in Holmes County, Robert Clark was jailed with his father, who was arrested on murder charges.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:53.000
The boy was released the next day.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:01.000
A white lawyer in the county seat of Lexington defended the father and won an acquittal on the grounds of self-defense.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:03.000
The year was 1940.

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Wow.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Tell us about that.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
Well, that is exactly right.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:27.000
I didn't know anything about what was going on, but we know we had lots of law enforcement officials here, and they not only carried me to jail and locked me up overnight.

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:33.000
But they kept my brother to jail and locked him up, like both of us.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:39.000
Well, tell us what happened. Why were they out here?

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:55.000
Well, they had found an individual dead about a couple of miles from here, not on our property, but off our property.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:00.000
And they suspicion that it was my father.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:08.000
But I was so small and young, and I didn't know what was going on.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:09.000
So he was acquitted?

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:10.000
Yes.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:14.000
But you spent, why do you think they put you in jail, too?

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Well, they not only put me in jail, my other brother. They put us in jail.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:29.000
Also, I really think they were just trying to intimidate us, but putting us in jail.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:38.000
You know, in the 1940s, at that time, I was 12 years old.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:47.000
Well, I assume that most of the time was somewhat calmer than that, though. Tell us what was like growing up here.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:54.000
Well, growing up here, we grew up on our own place.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:08:02.000
And I can truthfully say, I never worked on a plantation one day in the life.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:10.000
I never worked in a white man's cotton field one day in the life.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:23.000
But because we grew up on our own place, lots of blacks, most of the blacks, looked at us as being different.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:30.000
And I've always told them, I'm no different than you. All of us is one and the same.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:35.000
You are just as much as I am.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:43.000
And growing up here, we had to go to school. That was no if and end.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:52.000
School times may have been four months, five months. It all depends up on how early you got to cut and out of the fence.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:09:08.000
The four school would start because the white man did not want the black children on his plantation leaving the cotton field to go to school.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:27.000
And it all depends on the spring of the year, the temperature. If it got warm, then school closed because you want to feel and you sprouted and you knocked stocks and what have you.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:36.000
So I grew up with a four to five month school and grammar school.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:39.000
Where did you go to school? Where was the school?

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:48.000
I went to school, saw this flat. That's three miles this way. How did you get there?

00:09:48.000 --> 00:10:05.000
I had to walk there, range sleet of snow. We had to walk. And when my aunt's taught the school west of here, a whole city, which was two and a half mile, we went to school there for two years.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:24.000
But we had to, we could go through the field and if it didn't rain and get there. But if it rained, we had to go around the road to get there, which was three and a half mile.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:49.000
But one of the things my mother made sure that range sleet of snow that we never missed a day out of school. And since you ask about that, the white children would be riding buses and they'd come by throwing spitballs out after us.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:11:07.000
So I, you know, we get off behind my uncle and aunt who was schoolteaches and I would get a pocket of gravels. And when they would throw those spitballs off after me, then I'd throw those gravels back after them.

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:25.000
But I am proud to say at least two of those individuals have come to my house and have said right here in the same room where we are today asking me for my help to help them.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:37.000
Yes, I helped them. I didn't hold against them. But I did not to forget to remember. Do you remember when you threw a new spitballs off after me?

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:40.000
But that may have been a little uncomfortable.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.000
They just laughed at all.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:48.000
Was this a one room school house? Would you have one teacher or more than one teacher?

00:11:48.000 --> 00:12:00.000
It was two teachers. Two teachers. Two teachers, eight grade. And that was it. Now that was high school. I mean, that was grammar school.

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:11.000
But after high school, you had to bow it off from home because there was no buses to get African-Americans here in the school.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:15.000
How far away was the high school from here?

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:34.000
Sixteen miles, Lexington. The next one, 24, Durant. My first year, my uncle became the principal of Mount Olive, vocational, high school. That was north of Lexington.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:50.000
My ninth grade year, I stayed there in the teacher's home. But his family was multiplying very rapidly. And it wasn't enough room for me to stay there.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:13:01.000
So then, my tenth grade year, I enrolled in the Homes Kind of Training School, which is now William Sullivan at Durant.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:17.000
But every Monday morning, range sleet of snow, I step off of that porch, headed to pickin', just like I'm headed to my car shed, a car port.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:23.000
Headed to pickin', to kiss that 2am train to get to do rain.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:26.000
Wow. Range sleet of snow.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:35.000
You know, that is amazing, but also probably most of the people who did do didn't go to high school, did they?

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:38.000
They didn't go to high school. They did not go.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:42.000
But your parents really were insisting that you were going to go.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:54.000
They insisted that I was going to go. And after, you know, when I was 34, or yes, if they had not been to them, I would have dropped out of school.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:03.000
But after, you know, I had reached that age, I was determined that I was going to get an education.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:10.000
So here on the... What did you do? Did you have cattle farms?

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:30.000
We had cow, we had hogs, we had chickens, we had turkeys, we had geese, and of course we had the horses and mues, the horses and mues, the polar wagon, and the polar plow.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:46.000
And I started to make an a full day in the field when I was 7 years old, plowed when I was 7 years old, when I had to reach up for the plow house, over my head.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:55.000
And I can remember them, they'd always give the young-ish person what they call their old hay.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:10.000
That's, you know, an old-immune house. And the old house that they gave me when I first started, she didn't walk. She just tried it very fast.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:27.000
And I can remember one day when I was plowing and the plow hit a stump and the hound went up and hit me under the teeth and knocked me flat on my back.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:45.000
But one thing I knew, I knew that we had our farm, but I knew I was not going to farm for a living. But when I went to college, my aunts was farming, they had never been married.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:54.000
I was quick as I'd get out of college, I would come home and take care of that crop for them.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
What are the acres that you have here?

00:15:56.000 --> 00:16:01.000
It's 228 acres in the family place.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.000
That's a good size.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:22.000
228 acres in the family place. And I have bought 82 acres surrounding the family place, which was originally all of it was in the family.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:34.000
But some of it had gotten out of the family by some of the individuals dying and spouses married again and got out of the family.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:40.000
What was religion very important in your life? Education certainly was.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:48.000
Religion was very, very important. It was very, very important.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:57.000
And frankly speaking, I confess Christ at 3.5 years old and the individuals asked my mother,

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:15.000
she said, yes, he knows what he's doing. And I was the truth. My mother had not allowed me to be baptized.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:23.000
Because that's what I got at 3.5 years old. Have cared me thus far.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
Where did you go to church?

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:37.000
A pleasant green. That's a little church about two miles from here. A little wooden church. We're trying to rebuild a brick church.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:51.000
The only reason we have not rebuilt because my grandfather, when they built the church, you know, the white folk just let them build on their land.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:18:04.000
And you know, they built there. But we can't, we have no need to. So we can't rebuild them without these. So we're going to rebuild the church. Pleasant green.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:13.000
So you said I believe that you didn't have many experiences with whites growing up, that you were not on a plantation, that you were going to separate schools.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:24.000
Tell us a little bit about what segregation was like in this part of the world. Where did you become aware of that there were two different ways?

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:48.000
Well, my mother always told me and my brother, when we would leave here right on our horse is going to Ebenezer. Every time she would tell us, so now you're all as just as much as those white boys.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:19:00.000
She would call their name. She said, but you can't do this, you can't do that. She said, it's not right, but that's the law. And that's what you've got to do.

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:21.000
And I've been knowing, you know, segregation all of my life because since I was large enough, my folk taught me and I had a grandfather, my father's father, who was a slave in Hines County.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:38.000
And he was 11 years old at emancipation. And he told me about him, living never have worn a palpants until after slavery. He always wore something like our dress or gown.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:53.000
But when I got, you know, too large for them to carry me to church at night because I'd go to sleep and he was too old to walk to church at night.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:20:04.000
And when I was not large enough to go to the field and he was too old to go to the field, then they would leave him at home with me.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:21.000
But he told me as a child what slavery was like. And he says, young man, things is going to be better. But young men like you is going to have to grow up and make a difference.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:26.000
So, you had that from the very beginning.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:29.000
That from the very beginning.

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:39.000
So when you and your brother rode your horses into Ebenezer, what did you find there? What was it found like and what did you have to be careful about?

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:54.000
You had to be careful about that term. You didn't make any infuriate in a white person. You didn't say yes and no to any white person.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:21:08.000
You made sure you didn't look at a white lady. If she was coming, you turn your head because they may get upset about you looking at her.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:14.000
And she always told us.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:26.000
And we adhere to what she said. And I always knew. And that's one of the problems that we have today.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:30.000
And that's one of the things I'm going to be spending the rest of my life to work on.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:46.000
Many African Americans don't know who they are. Some African Americans right now. If a child is smart and and and done well in his books, they'll tell him you're trying to act like you white.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:57.000
And that's one of the things that we got to get rid of. But this is something I have known all of my life that I was equal to anybody.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:03.000
Not as smart as anybody, but I'm equal to anybody.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:10.000
When you finish high school then you decided to go into college and even fewer blacks were going to college at that point.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:21.000
And you chose Jackson State, which is a good distance from here, still within the state, within a couple hours, dry.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:29.000
But tell us what it was like your decision to go there and what was Jackson State like and just after we were born?

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:43.000
First of all, let me tell you, my first chance is to glue because I want to be a lawyer. You may have heard of Perry Howard, a pair of Howard, a little north of here between here and here in Evaneza.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:58.000
And I always want to be a lawyer. And I thought I had to major in pre-law to be a lawyer. And I wanted to enroll a to glue, but I wanted to be a work-age student.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:04.000
And the to glue told me that it would take me eight years to graduate if I be a work-age student.

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:13.000
So I decided to go to Jackson College. That's where my father had gone and some other folks.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:23.000
And my uncle wanted me to go to all-come. He was for a long time ago. But I know I didn't want nothing at parliament, so I didn't go to all-come.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:37.000
So I went over to my aunt's house, one I was telling you about. They gave me, I think, a dollar and a quarter that came back back, went down to my uncle Lewis's house.

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:48.000
That's a grand uncle of mine. And he gave me a dollar and fifth of cents. So I left here, hid it to Jackson College.

00:23:48.000 --> 00:24:01.000
It was Jackson College for Negro teachers at that time, with less than five dollars in my pocket. And I left here, walking, walked to pickings.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:17.000
I walked to pickings, called the bus. The trailway bus. And got rolled into Jackson. Then I called the 10 Length Meals Street bus and rolled out to Jackson College.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:30.000
So when I got out to Jackson College and I got ready to enroll, I told them I want to be a work-aid. I want to work my way. I don't have any money.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:38.000
They said, it takes money to go to Jackson State. If you only got no money, call your folks and tell your folks to come get you.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:52.000
I said, well, my folks don't have a phone. Well, I'll call a neighbor. Well, it's not in my neighbors' have a phone. So they say, we're going to put you up for the night.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:25:03.000
But if you only got no money when you get back to Guatemala, you're going to have to go home. All right. All the other students, you know, who went through Russia, and they got the meal ticket.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:13.000
But I went back to the barracks room 205, where they assigned me. And I stayed there all day. No food.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:26.000
So the next moment of the other kids was getting up, going to the dining hall. But I got up and went to the rest of the office. And I was sitting there reading the rest of the paper.

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:35.000
When the restaurant came in and the restaurant said, you have any money today? Said, no, sir. Don't.

00:25:35.000 --> 00:25:53.000
So we're going to send you down to the president's office. So we went out. They sent me down to Dr. Redrick's office. When I walked into his office, he said, young man, I'm going to stay in you wanting to go to college and don't have no money.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:26:10.000
Yes, sir. That's right. Don't you know it? Take money to go to college? I'll say yes, sir. I know that. He said, well, I'll tell you what, young man. You can lead a horse to the water, but you can't make him drink.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:22.000
He said, now we're going to give you a chance to get an education. But we can't get where we can't make you get one, but we're going to make sure we bump your heads against the wall.

00:26:22.000 --> 00:26:38.000
So what he worked out then was to work with the custodians on the yacht for 25 cents an hour. That would pay for half of my tuition.

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:54.000
And the other half, I had a job, a move in the garbage out of the women's dormitories, two women dormitories. And as God would have it to be, you know, I went through that year.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:27:07.000
And I participated in basketball. All right, I'm a functional and we just, you know, have followed the dogs all across the woods at night.

00:27:07.000 --> 00:27:19.000
And I went out for track and they asked me, what do you run? Well, I didn't know anything about no 220, 440 or anything like that. And I said, track.

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:30.000
I said, what do you run? I said, track. I said that because I didn't want to tell them I didn't know. They said, well, we go shoot what you run.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:41.000
So then they put me into, you know, start me out and I out ran everybody and everything except the hundred y'all days.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:28:06.000
So we got the conference championship that year in track. And then after that year, I was the first person to get a track scholarship in at Jackson State University, a full time track scholarship.

00:28:06.000 --> 00:28:11.000
And that's a very interesting story about what you had to go through just to be able to be there.

00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:18.000
That's right. What were your favorite subjects? What, you said you wanted to be a lawyer? Was that still your ambition now?

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:32.000
Well, I want to be a lawyer and the dean of students called me in to her office one day. And she pulled her eye glasses off and leaned over.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:48.000
And she said, young man, I see where you want to be a lawyer. I said, yes, ma'am. And she put her a finger so close to my nostrils until you couldn't get a straightener cat hair between them.

00:28:48.000 --> 00:29:02.000
She said, we are not going to let you use the teaching profession to become a lawyer. And if you want to become a lawyer, you pack your doors and get away from here.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:20.000
And I went back home, went back to the Dombatore and packed my clothes. She said, do it. But they never called me back. And after they didn't call me back a week or so, I packed them and just went on.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:30.000
But I didn't have anyone to tell me that I could have been a lawyer without majoring in pre-law.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:34.000
So you decided to become a teacher then?

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:53.000
Yes, sir. I decided to become a teacher because that's all preclared, all in African America do it. That time, Elz and Bina, Jonathan are going to the field.

00:29:53.000 --> 00:30:04.000
I see here where you left Jackson States before you actually graduated to teach second grade in Durant. And that you graduated in 1963.

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:05.000
1950.

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:09.000
Before you graduated to teach. Did you need the money or you wanted to?

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:22.000
No, sir. Let me tell you what happened. They had done my junior year. They implemented a program in help.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:43.000
And physical education. And the dean, Dean HT Sampton, set up a program for five of us. And we could, you know, graduate and get our degree and health and physical education.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:31:00.000
But we'll have to go back to school that summer. So it was four men, four male and one lady. And the lady met me on campus one day and said, hey, we're going to have to be here for five years.

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:06.000
That's what you mean we're going to be here for five years. She said, that's what Dean Sampton said.

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:21.000
So I went to Dean Sampton's office. As a dean, I have the grade point average. I have passed all of the tests. And I have done everything.

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:32.000
I have met all of the requirements that you set up. He said, well, clock, I'm sorry. I can't set up a program for one student.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:46.000
But I can set up a program for five. So when he said that I was going to have to stay there at fifth year, that's when I dropped out of school. She we were in our own quarters.

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:58.000
And that's when I dropped out of school at the end of the fall quarter. And I must have Sullivan where I finished high school.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:14.000
And she taught me to teach there. So that was the reason that I dropped out. I wasn't going to stay there five years because when you be there, you know, and students that have stayed there.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:25.000
And when they come back on the campus and see you there, when they come back to basketball game, hey, Grandpa, hey, Grandpa.

00:32:25.000 --> 00:32:34.000
But I had not flopped the thing. So you didn't get your degree that I did go back and get my degree there.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:46.000
And a year later in 1952, a year later, in 1952, one was a Brown versus Board of Education decision that came down to 54.

00:32:46.000 --> 00:33:01.000
What was the word around the community then? Was that a lot of publicity nationally about school integration? What was happening here?

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:27.000
The word was segregation now and segregation forever. And that was it. And they did not believe that Brown versus the Board of Education, they did not believe that they was going to have to adhere to it.

00:33:27.000 --> 00:33:41.000
And any individual that acted in a manner where they believed in that, those individuals was immediately released.

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:55.000
So the example over in the Delta, when I was teaching school over Louise, where they ate much school. But your first six weeks of two months would be half days.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:07.000
And then in the spring of the year, your last two months or six weeks would be half days. Because in the fall of the year, they'd be going home to pick cotton.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:24.000
And in the spring of the year, they'd be going home to go to the field. So when I had taught over Louise for seven years, the superintendent of education sent for me to come to his office.

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:43.000
I went after noon after school and I went to his office and said, yes sir, Mr. Brown, I'm the stand you want to see me. He said, yes, I heard that you said it would be all right for white children and black children to go to school together.

00:34:44.000 --> 00:35:02.000
I said, yes sir, Mr. Brown, I did serve that. And I said that the white parent need to explain to that children that is fine. And the black parent need to explain to that children that is fine.

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:25.000
He said, you really believe that, huh? I said, yes sir. He got up, put his hat on, walked out of his office and left me sitting in his office. But at the end of the school time, I got a message that I was no longer needed in the school system.

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:41.000
So just because you said that you were fired. This was a tough time because the next year in 1955, Emmett Till was murdered. Talk about your recollections of that and how you felt.

00:35:42.000 --> 00:36:00.000
Well, I knew it was wrong. I don't know the time, and Emmett Till was murdered. I was, you know, a high school official, I don't know, college official also. We were at the fall conference getting ready to workshop.

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:29.000
Father's Southwestern Athletic Conference when he got killed. But I was not a bit surprised. But one of the things, some of the things that happened in Louise, you know, around Louise after I left, I was glad that the prompts that the student time that did find me because some of the things that had happened to some of the other folks.

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:46.000
I had been putting lights and etc. and I was, you know, glad it did not happen to me. But at the same time when that happened to me, there was three gentlemen came to see me.

00:36:46.000 --> 00:37:05.000
One gentleman was just a parent. Quite, you wouldn't think he, you know, never said word if you don't say anything to him. The other gentleman had students going to school there and his wife also taught there.

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:26.000
And the other gentleman was a preacher. But he was a non-passon preacher. They came to see me. And at preacher told me, he said, I understand the sumpteen of don't want you. He said, you don't have to go nowhere. You know, he teaching the damn one of his kids.

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:44.000
I said, well, if he doesn't want me, I don't want to stay here. He said, but you ain't teaching his kid. But God put on my heart to go ahead and stay and to not fight it. And I was glad that I did.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:52.000
Well, I see in the 50s you taught for seven years at the Humphrey's County Training School of Adelta, is that correct?

00:37:52.000 --> 00:38:09.000
That was the Humphrey's County Training School of Adelta. And while I was at the Humphrey's County Training School of Adelta, I think a year was 19 and 56, I believe it was, 56, I'll flip to seven.

00:38:09.000 --> 00:38:24.000
But when we were getting ready for the baccalaught services, we went into Belzona, Meal, and another black instructor to get a hair trim that night.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:41.000
And when I got up out of the chair, Rubin Lee took my seat. He was sitting there waiting next. And when we got to the baccalaught services next morning, we had a young lady that lived in Belzona going to have a school.

00:38:41.000 --> 00:38:54.000
And she broke the news to us that Rubin Lee had been killed. You know, had been shot about two hours from the barbershop.

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:59.000
And he was shot because he was starting to ask people to register and vote.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:22.000
Because he was asking people to raise just a vote. And that's why he was shot in Kiev. And it is my understanding that some of the individuals that may have known something about it,

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:32.000
that the bossman gave them money to send them away from here.

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:40.000
And about that time, the citizens council had formed two in opposition to the Brown decision.

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:52.000
What, what, what, what citizens council? Was that a presence in your area where, were, were you aware of what they were doing? Is they tried to interfere in anything that you were doing?

00:39:52.000 --> 00:40:07.000
Yes, so I, I very much aware of the, the citizen council was ruling things then. Not the legislature and not the governor, but it was the citizen council ruling thing.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:36.000
And I happen to see in the, you know, they had the Soviet commission. I happen to see in that report some years later that superintendent of Humphers County reported to the Soviet commission that I have gotten rid of all of the troublemakers.

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:51.000
And I assume I was going to go shove them into what he was talking about. And, and another thing, this is not, you know, not talking about me. My father was a school teacher.

00:40:52.000 --> 00:41:08.000
He was fired in the Humphers County because he was teaching voter restoration classes. All right, he went to Madison County and taught at Madison, a, a Rosemaw school principal there for two years.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:31.000
And then he was fired there and he could not yet a never job in Mississippi. See what they would do, they would take your name and give your name to the Soviet commission, that sovereign commission, which, some of those names to all of the superintendents of education.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:40.000
We should probably say here that this sovereignty commission was an agency appointed by the state and it was really a secret police wasn't it?

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:41.000
That's right.

00:41:41.000 --> 00:41:45.000
And they have files on practically everybody. That's right.

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:55.000
So it was really dangerous to be a teacher and to say anything that went against the white supremacist system.

00:41:56.000 --> 00:42:09.000
Well, they, you know, most teachers, lots of teachers, you know, allow their main hood, a person hood to be taken from them.

00:42:09.000 --> 00:42:21.000
But never was I going to allow my main hood, my person hood, to be taken from me for a grandpa over over Louise.

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:32.000
When we got our first set of new books in the library, he set word down, I was a sister, Pruspa.

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:41.000
For that is a book in a library with the picture of a black rabbit and a white rabbit on the back of it.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:55.000
And for me to pull that book and bring it to his office immediately, say if black children see that, they will get the idea that they support the play with white children.

00:42:55.000 --> 00:43:00.000
And I sent word back to the student tender.

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:06.000
If you want that day, I'm book pulled, you'll have to come by here and pull it to yourself.

00:43:07.000 --> 00:43:17.000
Well, no, I, you know, that's, I guess, that laid up to my termination, which was fine.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:20.000
So it was just very difficult.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:29.000
Your father and you and probably others who dared to say what you meant and what you believed were likely to get in trouble in the day.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:42.000
And I remember my granddad, what I was talking about, when I was small, he'd get up in church and be telling folk about they should race the vote and do this and that and that.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:46.000
And I see folk walking out. I was about three or four years old.

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:50.000
Old main clogged, going to get somebody keel.

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:56.000
And I was wondering, you know, ain't a white folk here, how do you go know it?

00:43:56.000 --> 00:44:00.000
But I didn't know at that time that folk go back and tell white folk everything.

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:02.000
How many commission had black agents?

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:04.000
Oh, yes.

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:11.000
At some point you, when did you go to Michigan State for your masters and talk about what it was like?

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:13.000
No, no.

00:44:15.000 --> 00:44:16.000
Okay.

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:21.000
I had been taught all of my life.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:28.000
And psychology books had taught me that blacks are equal to whites.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:35.000
You know, ability is not given to raise creed of color.

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:44.000
And most of the blacks at that time was going to Tuskegee.

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:45.000
All right.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:51.000
And as you said a few minutes ago, lots of was flocking to Indiana.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:45:03.000
But I wanted to go to a place where I wanted to make sure to see if I measured up.

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:06.000
If I really was equal.

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:09.000
So I chose three schools.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:12.000
I chose Michigan State.

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:15.000
I chose Notre Dame.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:21.000
And I chose the University of California.

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:27.000
The University of California was so far because I didn't have money to get out there.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:36.000
I'd have to go to Jackson and make loans on the fun of tea I didn't have in my house.

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:42.000
And Notre Dame taught too much religion.

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:44.000
You know, I'm a Christian.

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:48.000
I went to get religion, but religion wasn't what I wanted.

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:52.000
So then that left Michigan State.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:56.000
So I went to Michigan State.

00:45:56.000 --> 00:46:01.000
And I guess we could point out here that there was no place in Mississippi where you could get a message.

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:04.000
There was no place in Mississippi.

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:07.000
I could go to get a master's degree.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:11.000
I had to leave the state of Mississippi to get the master's degree.

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:19.000
They would pay the state would pay the difference for you to go there and get a degree.

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:27.000
And done my last year at Michigan State.

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:34.000
One of the professors at Jackson State asked me about coming back there.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:39.000
And I tell him, no, I'm going to go ahead and finish my work at Michigan State.

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:43.000
He said, oh, you think they better than we are.

00:46:43.000 --> 00:46:46.000
I said, no, sir, but that's not it.

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:53.000
But I really wanted to see if I made it up to fight for a good night.

00:46:53.000 --> 00:46:56.000
I want to say I've been taught that all of my life.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:00.000
Well, they asked you to teach you in all white school.

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:04.000
Talk about that in the decision you made there.

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:06.000
Mac and I got all of it.

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:08.000
Yeah.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:10.000
I did Mac and I got all of it.

00:47:10.000 --> 00:47:18.000
I was all for the job up there to integrate the system up there.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:27.000
And he thought that I had better custom to integration and that I could stand it better.

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:30.000
And I first accepted the job.

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:37.000
But after thinking about it, I called and told him that I was not going to accept the job.

00:47:37.000 --> 00:47:43.000
And let me tell you about my first class at Michigan State University.

00:47:43.000 --> 00:47:46.000
I think class 35.

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:50.000
I was the only African-American in the class.

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:53.000
And the professor asked a question.

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:55.000
I can't remember what the question is.

00:47:55.000 --> 00:48:00.000
But I remember that question from maybe my sophomore year at Jackson State.

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:04.000
But I was too nervous to raise my hand.

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:08.000
One guy from West Coast raised his hand.

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:10.000
And I asked the question, I knew he's wrong.

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:12.000
The professor said no.

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:15.000
God from East Coast raised his hand.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:19.000
And I asked the question, I knew the professor said no.

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:23.000
By that time I learned to shake and hate and I got nervous.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:28.000
And I answered the question and he said, sir, you're correct.

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:32.000
And from that day on till this one.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:35.000
I have had no fear.

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:42.000
And that's why it did not book me when I went to the house of representatives,

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:46.000
a home of 22 members of home 21, they're quite.

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:50.000
That's why it did book me one bit.

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:52.000
So it was good that you got away.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:53.000
Yes sir.

00:48:53.000 --> 00:48:55.000
And saw what the competition was like.

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:56.000
That's right.

00:48:56.000 --> 00:48:58.000
Then you came back.

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:00.000
You turned down that job.

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:09.000
And from 1961 to 1966, you taught and coached at Lexington High School back in Holmes County.

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:13.000
And that was the period when the Civil Rights Movement really got underway here.

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:18.000
Tell us what you remember about those years, both in terms of your teaching

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:23.000
and in terms of what was going on in the community.

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:29.000
Well, I was teaching during that time.

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:37.000
And I do remember when the milestone 14

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:42.000
had missed my claim sent me uptown that day.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:44.000
This was when they decided to try to register.

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:47.000
Yeah, when they were side tried to register.

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:56.000
And I might reiterate here that my father and one other man, Black Man,

00:49:56.000 --> 00:50:00.000
were the last two names, Black names that they had raised off the books

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:03.000
because they didn't raise their cell.

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:12.000
And then when I found out about the Civil Rights Movement, I really didn't know about it.

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:20.000
And when I first tried to become a part of it, some of the Blacks thought

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:25.000
that the White folk were sending me to spy on them.

00:50:25.000 --> 00:50:32.000
And I really got into the movement through Henry and Schoo.

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:38.000
When I went to meet Henry and Schoo and talk to them.

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:42.000
We should probably point out these are the Lorenzies.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:47.000
These are the White couple who came from the White County in the fall of 1964.

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:49.000
That's right.

00:50:49.000 --> 00:51:00.000
And Henry and Schoo accepted me and then they gradually accepted me.

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:09.000
But they thought I was coming for, you know, to get the message and carry back to the White folk.

00:51:09.000 --> 00:51:11.000
Well, it was, yeah.

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:18.000
And when you were teaching at that time, were any of your students actively involved?

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:21.000
Did they see the Civil Rights Movement as something they wanted to do?

00:51:21.000 --> 00:51:22.000
Oh, yes.

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:25.000
I quite a few students actually involved.

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:29.000
One young man walked out of pitchfilt.

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:33.000
He was one of my football players.

00:51:33.000 --> 00:51:36.000
He went down, they punched him in his side.

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:41.000
And he had to mispronounce practice for about two weeks.

00:51:41.000 --> 00:51:46.000
And we had, you know, quite a few students that was involved.

00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:54.000
We had the Freedom Summer here in 1964, where a lot of students came down from the North.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:56.000
Many of them were white.

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:59.000
And about 30 of them were in Holmes County.

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:05.000
Do you remember Freedom Summer and the challenge of the Freedom Democratic Party?

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:06.000
Yes, sir.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:10.000
How do you remember the Freedom Summer?

00:52:10.000 --> 00:52:17.000
And the challenge of the Freedom Democratic Party in 1964.

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:22.000
But I was proud to be a part of the challenge in 1968.

00:52:22.000 --> 00:52:37.000
And then I, the legislature passed an act,

00:52:37.000 --> 00:52:44.000
allowing counters to have an adult to education program.

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:50.000
And I went to my superintendent and asked him,

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:54.000
he would implement an adult education program.

00:52:54.000 --> 00:53:00.000
Because our new men of the pound were not able to help their students with the lesson.

00:53:00.000 --> 00:53:03.000
And that would be better for the students.

00:53:03.000 --> 00:53:10.000
Well, he said, no, I don't think it's in the best interest of the county to do that.

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:16.000
I said, well, may I come before the boy?

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:20.000
He said, you can come and photo-boy, but don't bring no drool.

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:24.000
So I got two individuals to go with me.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:33.000
I got Mr. Laplace Polk, who was a social science teacher down at Chula,

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:35.000
as Marcial High School now.

00:53:35.000 --> 00:53:41.000
I got Mr. Curtis Lodge, who was a social science teacher over at Durant,

00:53:41.000 --> 00:53:43.000
which is William Sullivan.

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:45.000
And we went.

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:51.000
And I explained to the board what I wanted.

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:59.000
And the board says, we will have an adult education program when the student tell me, ask for one.

00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:05.000
I said, you mean it's a student tell me, ask for one, you will have one.

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:08.000
They say, they say, well, that's correct.

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:15.000
I said, well, next year, you will implement an adult education program,

00:54:15.000 --> 00:54:22.000
because I'm the clan of my canister for Sumetinder right now.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:35.000
So it was needless to say that at the end of the year, I got a message that my contract was not renewed.

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:37.000
I got it again.

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:42.000
All right, then we were the legislature with the incision.

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:45.000
We had two legislators.

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:51.000
Now, I'm running for Sumetinder of Education, but they get a local and private pass.

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:56.000
Now, the local and private, eventually, we, it has been ruled on constitutes.

00:54:56.000 --> 00:54:57.000
You can't do it now.

00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:09.000
But they draw up legislations like in a county where highway 12 and highway 17 intersects.

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:14.000
May appoint their Sumetinder.

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:22.000
And when they drew that up and got that pass, and I could not run for Sumetinder of Education.

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:27.000
And that's how I ran for the legislature.

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:29.000
I did really interesting.

00:55:29.000 --> 00:55:35.000
Before we get to that, there's something I really want to ask you because in 1965,

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:41.000
the Holmes County Schools were forced to desegregate the White Schools.

00:55:41.000 --> 00:55:48.000
How did that affect you and your students, and how did that play out over the next couple of years?

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:55.000
Was it successful? Did White students go to White Schools? Did White State?

00:55:55.000 --> 00:56:01.000
No White students went to Black schools.

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:08.000
Some of the students had to pay the price, and they had to pay a hell of a price.

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:13.000
One of the things we was talking about last night,

00:56:13.000 --> 00:56:22.000
was yesterday evening, planning the further civil rights celebration that we were having,

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:25.000
and we were talking about that.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:33.000
One young lady that went to school there,

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:38.000
she later went to school to me after I got five when I was teaching over at Saints.

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:43.000
But she said, Mr. Clark, you don't know how cruel it was.

00:56:43.000 --> 00:56:48.000
She said, I never will be the same again.

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:55.000
And it really had a heck of a impact on that particularly young lady.

00:56:55.000 --> 00:56:58.000
What did she have to face in White School?

00:56:58.000 --> 00:57:02.000
Was she just said it was cruel?

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:10.000
And you know, they were not treated like they were human beings.

00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:14.000
And I remember over at Durant,

00:57:14.000 --> 00:57:19.000
one young lady who lived in a rural area,

00:57:19.000 --> 00:57:22.000
Ms. Jarge Clark's daughter,

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:26.000
she was a superintendent of school one day,

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:29.000
and she ate mine from home.

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:37.000
But we gave him all kinds of trouble about just putting that young lady out.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:41.000
And I don't think he ever did that again.

00:57:41.000 --> 00:57:45.000
From 1966 to 1967,

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:53.000
you worked for Dr. Aurelia Mallory as director of all education at Saints' New York College in Lexington.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:58.000
Tell us about Dr. Mallory and Saints in your time there.

00:57:58.000 --> 00:58:05.000
Well, the superintendent, you know, fired me.

00:58:05.000 --> 00:58:08.000
Okay, that was good.

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:12.000
It really was the superintendent that was God in God's playing.

00:58:12.000 --> 00:58:16.000
Because I wanted an adult education program, right?

00:58:16.000 --> 00:58:20.000
When I started working for Dr. Aurelia Mallory,

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:29.000
she had 300 adults coming in six days a week,

00:58:29.000 --> 00:58:33.000
four o'clock from Monday, four to nine,

00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:36.000
from Monday through Friday.

00:58:36.000 --> 00:58:41.000
And then all sevens that come in for vocation,

00:58:41.000 --> 00:58:44.000
from nine until Twil.

00:58:44.000 --> 00:58:48.000
So when I went over there,

00:58:48.000 --> 00:58:53.000
she started me out as the coordinator of the program.

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:56.000
Then within about three months,

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:59.000
I was made director of the program.

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:04.000
So that was God's way of moving me

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:09.000
and putting me in charge of those adults.

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:13.000
And we had adult education programs on Saint-June College campus,

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:17.000
where it saw him at the church in Lexington, Asia.

00:59:17.000 --> 00:59:21.000
We had a class in Pickens.

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:23.000
We had a class in West,

00:59:23.000 --> 00:59:27.000
and we had a class in Chula also.

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:35.000
And one of the things about that when I ran against Jeppe Love and Warren,

00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:42.000
Jeppe Love, one of his challenges was that I had forced signatures.

00:59:42.000 --> 00:59:49.000
It's because that's one of my hands on that his name is there.

00:59:49.000 --> 00:59:52.000
And I know he can't read and write.

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:58.000
But what Mr. Love did not know that he had gone to adult schools

00:59:58.000 --> 01:00:00.000
that I was heading,

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:05.000
and they had taught him how to read and write.

01:00:05.000 --> 01:00:07.000
That's wonderful.

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:11.000
And what if we could take a short break here?

01:00:11.000 --> 01:00:15.000
There were a lot of political developments going on in the mid-60s.

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:19.000
One of them was Living Johnson's Great Society.

01:00:19.000 --> 01:00:23.000
And out of that came the idea of the community action boards,

01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:27.000
the cat boards that were supposed to be composed of local people

01:00:27.000 --> 01:00:32.000
who would be implementing various government and other programs.

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:37.000
And you were a briefly a member of that cat board in 1966.

01:00:37.000 --> 01:00:40.000
Talk about your experience there.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:45.000
Yes, I was a member of the cat board.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:56.000
And frankly speaking, that's when we had the first integrated meeting in the county

01:00:56.000 --> 01:01:04.000
at the courthouse when we had blacks and whites sitting around the table.

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:11.000
That's when we became a part of Central Mississippi and cooperating.

01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:22.000
And we were fortunate to get to white men to sit around the table with us.

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:27.000
But let me get off point a little bit.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:29.000
You can get the back on point.

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:34.000
But one of the things that I remember most about that,

01:01:34.000 --> 01:01:44.000
that night I guess I made about 100 gallons of water with drink and I read Fowlton that night by black folk.

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:50.000
Because they had never been able to drink all red fowls up before.

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:54.000
I never tasted any beer.

01:01:54.000 --> 01:01:57.000
So that was the first integrated meeting?

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:08.000
No, I heard that you weren't entirely happy with what the direction of that board is at, true.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:17.000
I'm not at all happy with the direction way the board going now.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:25.000
I see the civil rights movement that started in Homes County.

01:02:25.000 --> 01:02:35.000
And we always said the cause is more important than any individual.

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:42.000
And we're supposed to be working for the cause and not working for a vice-seer.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:49.000
We're not supposed to develop an idea and said, I want to do this.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:53.000
And it's going to be done my way, I know it.

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:58.000
And if individuals cannot reach a compromise,

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:06.000
and frankly speaking, I got a letter draft now that I have not had typed up yet.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:11.000
That is going to come from me in the Freedom Democratic Party of Homes County.

01:03:11.000 --> 01:03:17.000
And it's going to be calling on individuals elected officials in Homes County.

01:03:17.000 --> 01:03:24.000
You either do your job, if you can't do your job, then you need to resign.

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:27.000
You need to resign.

01:03:27.000 --> 01:03:36.000
And the CAP program, it went well, of a number of years.

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:42.000
First of all, it started out as a social program.

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:49.000
And it started out to get smarter, used to being a way home from Mama.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:54.000
Before he, she went to school and he wouldn't be a school crying from Mama.

01:03:54.000 --> 01:04:00.000
Then it gave individuals jobs who had never had jobs before.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:04.000
But one of the things I did when I was old at Saints,

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:09.000
was about the Maori had her approval of course.

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:19.000
And I was with Russ College, developed a giant program to have night school for those head start teachers.

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:28.000
Because I wanted those head start teachers to do more than just go there and babysit and play.

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:33.000
But you know, that should have been done statewide.

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:38.000
But it was just done on a small scale.

01:04:38.000 --> 01:04:49.000
The great society, the Lyndon Johnson started a particular ally with the head start program.

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:54.000
If I am one thing, I know I am an educator.

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:59.000
It may have been sometimes outside of school, but I know I am an educator.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:06.000
And head start needs to be a pre-K school.

01:05:06.000 --> 01:05:09.000
A pre-K program.

01:05:09.000 --> 01:05:18.000
Because children starting to school, first grade, and can't read, don't know as letters.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:22.000
Here she's starting off behind and they don't always be behind.

01:05:22.000 --> 01:05:24.000
They ain't never going to catch up.

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:27.000
Very strong.

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:35.000
You mentioned that you were going to run for County Superintendent and then they made that temporarily,

01:05:35.000 --> 01:05:37.000
