01:17:37.000 --> 01:17:44.000
And by that time Bill Monter said, okay, go ahead and do it. You're doing what they want you to do.

01:17:44.000 --> 01:17:53.000
You were just ready to walk out. I was ready to walk out. Walk out. And when Bill Monter said, you're doing what they want you to do.

01:17:53.000 --> 01:18:00.000
And when he said that, I dropped my hand and walked back in. And when I walked back in on the floor of the house,

01:18:00.000 --> 01:18:10.000
man, they was having a hooray. They was whoo-fisland, they was clapping and they was doing everything.

01:18:10.000 --> 01:18:17.000
And when I walked back in, they got just a cry.

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:27.000
That's right. But what I did when I first went to the legislature, you know, I had the school and that helped me.

01:18:27.000 --> 01:18:34.000
You know, I prepared myself for what legislation was coming up. And what I was going to do,

01:18:34.000 --> 01:18:42.000
sometimes I did just like a dinner at Michigan State, a Western Michigan, a Sydney burning midnight hour.

01:18:42.000 --> 01:18:51.000
So I would be prepared. And if they did agree with me, they knew that they couldn't share his wrong.

01:18:51.000 --> 01:18:52.000
They were at the news when I was talking about it.

01:18:52.000 --> 01:19:01.000
How long was it before somebody asked you for your vote?

01:19:01.000 --> 01:19:04.000
Maybe about eight years. Really? Maybe about eight years?

01:19:04.000 --> 01:19:18.000
That's that long. Yes, sir. And after eight years, we got the group in Jackson elected.

01:19:18.000 --> 01:19:19.000
Red Bay.

01:19:19.000 --> 01:19:23.000
Group of Black electors are basically enjoying you.

01:19:23.000 --> 01:19:25.000
In the state legislation?

01:19:25.000 --> 01:19:33.000
Yes, sir. You got three from Jackson elected. They did redistricted and got them re-elected.

01:19:33.000 --> 01:19:46.000
But after some of those issues, you know, I would speak out on them, some of the technical issues,

01:19:46.000 --> 01:20:02.000
and I could present myself on them. And some of those same elderly white gentlemen that, you know, were the pose to me being seated.

01:20:02.000 --> 01:20:10.000
Now, some folks say I was being an unketone for doing it. But sometimes they would know what's going on.

01:20:10.000 --> 01:20:16.000
And when time came to vote, they'd be jumping up trying to get my teaching.

01:20:16.000 --> 01:20:24.000
And if he's supposed to vote I, I'd tell him I, if he's supposed to vote no, I'd point to my nostrils.

01:20:24.000 --> 01:20:27.000
These are your younger colleagues in the Cappuella.

01:20:27.000 --> 01:20:32.000
Well, now these are some of the older, older white gentlemen.

01:20:32.000 --> 01:20:35.000
I see. So that's a big change.

01:20:35.000 --> 01:20:44.000
They're older white gentlemen. That's my summer. Black folk was telling me that, you know, I've been an unketone.

01:20:44.000 --> 01:20:50.000
But I didn't do them like they did me.

01:20:50.000 --> 01:20:58.000
In particular, I lived somebody come up like the gentleman from Vicksburg, with real sharp.

01:20:58.000 --> 01:21:05.000
The gentleman from the Luxe, real sharp, gentleman from Greenville, real sharp.

01:21:05.000 --> 01:21:12.000
And if they had something and they didn't know, they looked to me for me to direct them.

01:21:12.000 --> 01:21:19.000
But the true feels are never directed one in the wrong manner.

01:21:19.000 --> 01:21:30.000
And the first seatmate that I had, his white seatmate, then when it come up, he'd ask me how to vote the vote.

01:21:30.000 --> 01:21:34.000
If he's supposed to vote no, I'd say he's supposed to vote no.

01:21:34.000 --> 01:21:39.000
And then finally he asked me, he said, I want to ask you one thing.

01:21:39.000 --> 01:21:46.000
What you trying to do, get me defeated. That's a what you're talking about.

01:21:46.000 --> 01:22:00.000
You tell me to vote one way and you vote another. I said, hey, old man, I'm trying to tell you how to vote, how your vote back home won't you to vote.

01:22:00.000 --> 01:22:10.000
Well, about 10 years after you were first elected, you were appointed chairman of the House Education Committee.

01:22:10.000 --> 01:22:17.000
How did that happen? I mean, here nobody would talk to you and now you're in the chair of an important committee.

01:22:17.000 --> 01:22:20.000
Tell us how, what has happened before that could happen.

01:22:20.000 --> 01:22:28.000
All right, that is very interesting. That is very interesting.

01:22:28.000 --> 01:22:37.000
When CB Betten Newman was running far, Speaker Pro Tem, ought to fill in far,

01:22:37.000 --> 01:22:44.000
when John Junkin got sick, John Junkin was the speaker.

01:22:44.000 --> 01:22:51.000
So, Betten Newman met me on the first floor of the Capitol.

01:22:51.000 --> 01:23:02.000
I happened following a group, a so-called Libras, my good friend, but they'd all get good appointments and I'd wind up with nothing.

01:23:02.000 --> 01:23:17.000
So, Betten Newman asked me and met me on the first floor and he said, I need one more signal to and I will have a majority.

01:23:17.000 --> 01:23:27.000
And can I get you to sign it? I said, let me see it and I looked at it and I saw he needed one more.

01:23:27.000 --> 01:23:37.000
And I thought about, I was thinking about. All these years, I'm not following my other boys that I've been following and they get it burned and I don't get nothing.

01:23:37.000 --> 01:23:51.000
I'm going to look out for myself. So, I saw that I signed it and when I signed it, he dropped to one knee and he said,

01:23:51.000 --> 01:23:58.000
who, he dropped to one knee and he kissed that pin that I signed it with.

01:23:58.000 --> 01:24:07.000
And he said, who ever thought that white may be on his knee to a nigger?

01:24:07.000 --> 01:24:17.000
And I said, let's speak, you Peckaborch, you have to do a lot more of that from Black folks and the future.

01:24:17.000 --> 01:24:19.000
And what about you, what was the sacred day?

01:24:19.000 --> 01:24:26.000
Betten Newman, Betten Newman. And I signed that.

01:24:26.000 --> 01:24:37.000
Then, Betten I became, well, we could communicate. We could communicate to each other, with each other.

01:24:37.000 --> 01:24:45.000
And then, after Johnkins died, Betten became Speaker.

01:24:45.000 --> 01:24:55.000
I wanted Betten to appoint me as Chairman of Wildlife and Fisheries. He said, no, I got something else for you, better than that.

01:24:55.000 --> 01:25:00.000
So, he appointed me Vice Chairman of Education.

01:25:01.000 --> 01:25:14.000
All right. President Carter was elected. And George Rogers, who was the child person, he was appointed to President Carter's cabinet.

01:25:14.000 --> 01:25:23.000
All right, Aaron Henry was convening the State NAACP Convention in Vicksburg.

01:25:23.000 --> 01:25:29.000
And that's in Betten Newman District. He lived in the Queen of County. But his district was Vicksburg.

01:25:30.000 --> 01:25:40.000
So, I went, Aaron invited me to be the keynote speaker. And I spoke and I told Black folks,

01:25:40.000 --> 01:25:49.000
as time for you to get up and do something for yourself, don't sit around and wait for White folks to be giving you a hand up.

01:25:49.000 --> 01:25:51.000
Get up and do something for yourself.

01:25:52.000 --> 01:26:03.000
Lord, behold, the next day in the paper and bold headlight, potential Negro chair gives Black Power Speak.

01:26:05.000 --> 01:26:14.000
So, I just knew it was all over. So, about 10 days, Betten Newman sent for me to come to his office.

01:26:14.000 --> 01:26:21.000
So, when I went to his office, he had three boxes, about that high, sitting on his desk.

01:26:21.000 --> 01:26:31.000
And he opened one of the boxes and pulled one of the papers out and said, take that look at that.

01:26:31.000 --> 01:26:35.000
I want you to see that. I looked at it.

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:42.000
I said, well, yes, I'm a speaker. I did. I gave the speech. I said it.

01:26:42.000 --> 01:26:49.000
He said, what I call you in here to tell you that there ain't no vacancy yet.

01:26:49.000 --> 01:26:56.000
But when there is a vacancy, I will approach you.

01:26:56.000 --> 01:27:10.000
And that really changed my attitude towards him, with him having the pride to override all those spoken as district and to do that.

01:27:11.000 --> 01:27:21.000
That was something that I think is for and that you did what you had to do to become chair of the Education Committee.

01:27:21.000 --> 01:27:30.000
And as a result of that, you were responsible for, along with others, for pushing through one of the most important pieces of legislation.

01:27:31.000 --> 01:27:36.000
I think a long, long time. And that was the Education Reform Act.

01:27:36.000 --> 01:27:47.000
Tell us about William Witter, I think, with Governor Ben. Tell us about that debate and what the act does for a bid for the state.

01:27:47.000 --> 01:27:59.000
All right. As we get into that, before that, a white lawyer from Lexington had to call me and tell me what's coming up on the floor and part of it.

01:28:00.000 --> 01:28:05.000
I was trying to get on the inside.

01:28:05.000 --> 01:28:11.000
I went to the legislature as an education legislator.

01:28:11.000 --> 01:28:21.000
And I had been pushing for education, progressive education, first bail introduced when I went to Dr. King's field in Atlanta.

01:28:21.000 --> 01:28:24.000
They called a bail up and killed at that date.

01:28:25.000 --> 01:28:33.000
All right. Then after Governor William Witter became governor, which was great.

01:28:33.000 --> 01:28:47.000
And then he, we worked out a bill with him and we put together a bill, education reform, we call it.

01:28:48.000 --> 01:28:55.000
And I would make sure that I would get my bills out first.

01:28:55.000 --> 01:29:02.000
You know, the bills come out and be on the calendar, calling to how they come out of the committee.

01:29:02.000 --> 01:29:13.000
But the Rouge Committee had the authority at that time to rearrange the bill, the calendar, and they could kick the bill to the Hill of the Committee.

01:29:13.000 --> 01:29:19.000
So I met an 82 meeting before we went into the session.

01:29:19.000 --> 01:29:24.000
And we got our bill out the first week in the session.

01:29:24.000 --> 01:29:31.000
All right. Then they constantly kicked the bill back to the Hill of the Cal.

01:29:31.000 --> 01:29:34.000
Kick it back to the Hill of the Cal.

01:29:34.000 --> 01:29:42.000
So getting near the end of the session, I got my vice chairman, who was a white person.

01:29:42.000 --> 01:29:52.000
And another individual who was a very conservative, but he's a white person, but he's a poser.

01:29:52.000 --> 01:29:55.000
And we went to the Speaker's office.

01:29:55.000 --> 01:30:10.000
I said, Ms. Speaker, I can't be your office to let you know that I'm going to call this bill, I gave a number to bill, up for a meeting consideration.

01:30:10.000 --> 01:30:14.000
He says, I hope you wouldn't do that.

01:30:14.000 --> 01:30:20.000
I said, well, the time has arrived, Ms. Speaker, for us to do that.

01:30:20.000 --> 01:30:24.000
And he said, some of these boys can't stand the heat.

01:30:24.000 --> 01:30:30.000
I said, Mr. Speaker, they ain't supposed to be no boys on the floor of the house.

01:30:30.000 --> 01:30:33.000
If there's any boys, they're supposed to go home.

01:30:34.000 --> 01:30:40.000
And I shook his hand and I said, I'm going to make the motion.

01:30:40.000 --> 01:30:42.000
He says, I'm not going to recognize you.

01:30:42.000 --> 01:30:43.000
I said, thank you.

01:30:43.000 --> 01:30:46.000
Then my vice chairman said the same thing.

01:30:46.000 --> 01:30:52.000
He said, Mr. Speaker, if you don't recognize him, I'm going to make the motion.

01:30:52.000 --> 01:30:59.000
So then we went to the Florida House and we began to, you know, convene.

01:30:59.000 --> 01:31:03.000
At the proper time I stood it, made the motion.

01:31:03.000 --> 01:31:08.000
What does the gentleman from home wish to be recognized for?

01:31:08.000 --> 01:31:16.000
Ms. Speaker, the call house bill, such as such a number, up to the top of the calendar for a meeting consideration, rapped together.

01:31:16.000 --> 01:31:20.000
You're out of order, you're not recognized.

01:31:20.000 --> 01:31:26.000
And then my vice chairman did the same thing.

01:31:26.000 --> 01:31:29.000
All right, and he did the same thing to him.

01:31:29.000 --> 01:31:36.000
All right, then the house got in search of uproar until they just had to a join.

01:31:36.000 --> 01:31:48.000
But during that same time, I was seen letters that one of my colleagues from Cleveland, Mississippi, had brought white colleague,

01:31:48.000 --> 01:31:53.000
what we're going to do to your wife and your family if you vote for that bill.

01:31:53.000 --> 01:32:03.000
I had seen a letter from one of my colleagues in Yazoo City, what we're going to do to your wife and family.

01:32:03.000 --> 01:32:13.000
I had seen a letter from one of my colleagues out in East West Jackson, in Clinton.

01:32:13.000 --> 01:32:16.000
That's why he's really from Clinton.

01:32:16.000 --> 01:32:19.000
That's what we're going to do to your wife and family.

01:32:19.000 --> 01:32:21.000
Now who was writing these letters?

01:32:21.000 --> 01:32:24.000
And these were letters to people who were supporting the education?

01:32:24.000 --> 01:32:29.000
Let us to people on my committee who were supporting me.

01:32:29.000 --> 01:32:38.000
These would be from people back in their home telling them what they're going to do to their family.

01:32:38.000 --> 01:32:41.000
But they didn't have no names on them.

01:32:41.000 --> 01:32:51.000
So then at the end of that session, I went to Governor William Wattas office.

01:32:51.000 --> 01:33:07.000
I said, Governor Wattas, I said, if we can't get some kind of support, I don't know if I can keep on putting my members through this blood bath again.

01:33:08.000 --> 01:33:10.000
And he said, what we need to do.

01:33:10.000 --> 01:33:13.000
I said, you need to take it to the people.

01:33:13.000 --> 01:33:17.000
I said, you need to take it to some of the old line organizations.

01:33:17.000 --> 01:33:21.000
Like the Mississippi Southern Baptist, like the Farm Bureau.

01:33:21.000 --> 01:33:25.000
And we had that conversation.

01:33:25.000 --> 01:33:29.000
And that was the only conversation me and him had.

01:33:29.000 --> 01:33:34.000
So when I was a campaigner for Congress, I laid it to.

01:33:34.000 --> 01:33:38.000
And I jumped it to go to his meeting.

01:33:38.000 --> 01:33:43.000
He was having a Greenville at the Convention and Visitors Bureau.

01:33:43.000 --> 01:33:48.000
But I couldn't get within three blocks of their Convention Center.

01:33:48.000 --> 01:33:51.000
It was so many folks there.

01:33:51.000 --> 01:33:58.000
So after he had those meetings, he summoned six legislators.

01:33:58.000 --> 01:34:01.000
Three members of the House.

01:34:01.000 --> 01:34:04.000
And three members of the Senate.

01:34:04.000 --> 01:34:06.000
Two, they're in the mansion.

01:34:06.000 --> 01:34:08.000
Governor's Mansion.

01:34:08.000 --> 01:34:17.000
And he says, I'm not calling your here to ask your if I should call a space association.

01:34:17.000 --> 01:34:24.000
He said, but I'm calling your here to let your know I'm going to have a press conference.

01:34:24.000 --> 01:34:26.000
I'm going to get a date.

01:34:26.000 --> 01:34:34.000
And at that time, I will announce if I will call a space association or not.

01:34:34.000 --> 01:34:37.000
So that was the essence of that meeting.

01:34:37.000 --> 01:34:39.000
So shut up.

01:34:39.000 --> 01:34:44.000
Governor Wetter called the space association.

01:34:44.000 --> 01:34:46.000
All right.

01:34:46.000 --> 01:34:51.000
The speaker, Mr. Speaker.

01:34:51.000 --> 01:35:00.000
He summoned the same three legislators, members of the House to the Lieutenant Governor's Office.

01:35:00.000 --> 01:35:09.000
And the Lieutenant Governor summoned the same three members of the Senate that had met with the Governor.

01:35:09.000 --> 01:35:12.000
And they had a discussion.

01:35:12.000 --> 01:35:15.000
And the other discussion was constitutionally.

01:35:15.000 --> 01:35:22.000
If he called the session constitutionally, we got to convene.

01:35:22.000 --> 01:35:27.000
But the consensus was, among them, we don't have to do anything.

01:35:27.000 --> 01:35:36.000
So finally, Mr. Speaker said to me, Mr. Chairman, you might have saw it over there.

01:35:36.000 --> 01:35:39.000
What do you got to say about this?

01:35:40.000 --> 01:35:42.000
I said, Mr. President, I'm talking about the newman.

01:35:42.000 --> 01:35:49.000
Mr. Speaker, I serve at your will in pleasure.

01:35:49.000 --> 01:36:05.000
And if you have not removed me when the Governor calls a space association, I'm going to do everything I can to get a bill out of that house, out of the committee and get a pass.

01:36:05.000 --> 01:36:07.000
And I turned to the Lieutenant Governor.

01:36:07.000 --> 01:36:13.000
I said, Mr. Governor, and she goes, look, might have paid if I sent a bill over there.

01:36:13.000 --> 01:36:22.000
And if they know about it over there, but the news media and impede chairs.

01:36:22.000 --> 01:36:24.000
So that was it.

01:36:24.000 --> 01:36:27.000
And he did not remove me.

01:36:28.000 --> 01:36:36.000
And as the bill, that was a section of the bill of what I didn't want in the taxes.

01:36:36.000 --> 01:36:37.000
All right.

01:36:37.000 --> 01:36:46.000
And then after bills passed both houses, we met in the education committee room.

01:36:46.000 --> 01:36:48.000
That's the conference committee.

01:36:49.000 --> 01:36:58.000
If you meet on the Senate side, the chairman of Senate Education Committee chair for the House chair chair.

01:36:58.000 --> 01:37:02.000
So I was chairing the conference committee room, not meeting.

01:37:02.000 --> 01:37:04.000
I call it the order.

01:37:04.000 --> 01:37:11.000
So some of the Ellis Bowdron, blind son, but some others he could be.

01:37:11.000 --> 01:37:13.000
You know who he is.

01:37:14.000 --> 01:37:33.000
He says, Mr. Chairman, gentlemen from one, I suggest that we go around the table and see what parameters we are going to work with then, what we are going to take and what we are not going to take.

01:37:33.000 --> 01:37:36.000
And I suggest we start with you.

01:37:37.000 --> 01:37:39.000
I hadn't thought about one bit.

01:37:39.000 --> 01:37:45.000
I was thinking, I will not accept any taxes that I went on to give my speech.

01:37:45.000 --> 01:37:50.000
And he says, what about one sentence?

01:37:50.000 --> 01:37:54.000
I think I will not accept any taxes.

01:37:54.000 --> 01:37:57.000
What about one half percent?

01:37:57.000 --> 01:38:00.000
I think the gentleman from one very smart.

01:38:00.000 --> 01:38:03.000
I think he knows one half is taxes.

01:38:03.000 --> 01:38:06.000
Then I realized what I had done.

01:38:06.000 --> 01:38:10.000
I had put myself into a jail.

01:38:10.000 --> 01:38:14.000
So we stayed tied up for three weeks.

01:38:14.000 --> 01:38:16.000
They were trying to kill a bill.

01:38:16.000 --> 01:38:25.000
Now, Mr. Speaker, first time he ever did this, he put the chairman of ways of means on that because it was money.

01:38:25.000 --> 01:38:27.000
He always do that.

01:38:27.000 --> 01:38:29.000
Okay, that's good.

01:38:29.000 --> 01:38:34.000
But then he put somebody on there who was opposed to it.

01:38:34.000 --> 01:38:37.000
That's the gentleman from Grenada.

01:38:37.000 --> 01:38:41.000
So he was trying to stack the committee on us.

01:38:41.000 --> 01:38:50.000
So after we had met and met and met for three weeks, then Mr. Speaker, Betany Newman, says,

01:38:50.000 --> 01:38:55.000
when you meet a long time on legislation like Betany,

01:38:55.000 --> 01:38:58.000
it has a tendency to kill it.

01:38:58.000 --> 01:39:05.000
If you want your old bad bill, you better go ahead and try to work somewhere to get it out.

01:39:05.000 --> 01:39:12.000
But what I did not do, what I did, I still helped out for no taxes.

01:39:12.000 --> 01:39:15.000
But I got with one of the senators.

01:39:15.000 --> 01:39:18.000
And I worked out a plane with one of the senators.

01:39:18.000 --> 01:39:24.000
And let the senator present that to the committee, to the committee.

01:39:24.000 --> 01:39:31.000
And let the senator give us speech on that, like he is talking to me.

01:39:31.000 --> 01:39:35.000
Now, I didn't work this out, I didn't give it to the senator.

01:39:35.000 --> 01:39:37.000
Now, why didn't you want taxes?

01:39:37.000 --> 01:39:38.000
I mean, this is a program.

01:39:38.000 --> 01:39:39.000
Pardon?

01:39:39.000 --> 01:39:41.000
Why didn't you want to raise taxes?

01:39:41.000 --> 01:39:49.000
Well, at that time, I felt that we had the money to do it.

01:39:49.000 --> 01:39:53.000
And taxes were just a way to kill it.

01:39:53.000 --> 01:40:00.000
And if we were, you know, money for everything else, why we can't have money for education?

01:40:00.000 --> 01:40:01.000
No, no, no.

01:40:01.000 --> 01:40:02.000
No, no, no.

01:40:02.000 --> 01:40:06.000
What that bill did when it became law?

01:40:06.000 --> 01:40:12.000
Well, it compulsed the school of talents.

01:40:12.000 --> 01:40:16.000
Now, that bill had been repealed around the time of the Brown decision.

01:40:16.000 --> 01:40:17.000
It was that law.

01:40:17.000 --> 01:40:19.000
They were used to be compulsory incentives.

01:40:19.000 --> 01:40:20.000
Yes, sir.

01:40:20.000 --> 01:40:22.000
And then school and immigration came along.

01:40:22.000 --> 01:40:27.000
And so, so there was, Mississippi, I think, was the only state in union without a compulsory attendance.

01:40:27.000 --> 01:40:30.000
There was all the state and the nice without a compulsory school law.

01:40:30.000 --> 01:40:38.000
We were the, maybe the first state to pass one and the first state to repeal it.

01:40:38.000 --> 01:40:48.000
I think we first passed one in 1924 if my memory served me correctly.

01:40:48.000 --> 01:40:51.000
And what else did the new bill do?

01:40:51.000 --> 01:40:54.000
Early childhood education.

01:40:54.000 --> 01:40:56.000
So it was kindergarten?

01:40:56.000 --> 01:40:59.000
Yeah, kindergarten.

01:40:59.000 --> 01:41:06.000
It was a bill that, well, you told us how difficult it was to get fast.

01:41:06.000 --> 01:41:11.000
But just tremendously important in terms of where the state was going.

01:41:11.000 --> 01:41:20.000
And as the education person on the committee in the legislature, why you were instrumental in many of it happened?

01:41:20.000 --> 01:41:23.000
Well, yes, sir.

01:41:23.000 --> 01:41:27.000
You know, it was my, my teaching.

01:41:27.000 --> 01:41:36.000
I had not, for example, one time before Governor Winter.

01:41:36.000 --> 01:41:41.000
They would, as the education committee, third of one, individuals.

01:41:41.000 --> 01:41:44.000
I was not chairman then.

01:41:44.000 --> 01:41:51.000
And they would get up and leave so to make sure we wouldn't have a majority.

01:41:51.000 --> 01:42:01.000
But what I did, I had my individuals, some in the cloakroom, some in the closet, some in the bathroom.

01:42:01.000 --> 01:42:03.000
And they were counting.

01:42:03.000 --> 01:42:07.000
And when they got up and left, I went knocked on the doors.

01:42:07.000 --> 01:42:09.000
And I knocked on the door.

01:42:09.000 --> 01:42:12.000
They came back and we had a majority.

01:42:12.000 --> 01:42:19.000
And I moved that we would bring the bills to the top of the calendar for immediate consideration.

01:42:19.000 --> 01:42:21.000
I was not chairman then.

01:42:21.000 --> 01:42:25.000
Somebody else was chairman for immediate consideration.

01:42:25.000 --> 01:42:28.000
And they looked around and said, well, you got them a job.

01:42:28.000 --> 01:42:30.000
They just go, how to carry it.

01:42:30.000 --> 01:42:33.000
So we got it out of the committee.

01:42:33.000 --> 01:42:35.000
And that was it.

01:42:35.000 --> 01:42:39.000
But one end of the day, you came back to the committee room the other day.

01:42:39.000 --> 01:42:44.000
When he found out that Bill had been called, he got up on that table.

01:42:44.000 --> 01:42:48.000
And he walked down that table, stonking and excreming.

01:42:48.000 --> 01:42:52.000
That's because that bill had been brought out of the committee.

01:42:52.000 --> 01:42:56.000
Well, thank you so much for going into this detail.

01:42:56.000 --> 01:42:58.000
This is important for this door, it's a record.

01:42:58.000 --> 01:43:07.000
We've kept you long enough, but I can't let you go without asking you about your two campaigns for Congress,

01:43:07.000 --> 01:43:10.000
or the U.S. House of Representatives.

01:43:10.000 --> 01:43:18.000
What made you decide to run for Congress and talk us a little bit about those campaigns?

01:43:18.000 --> 01:43:29.000
Well, the reason I decided to run for Congress, I wanted to direct,

01:43:29.000 --> 01:43:39.000
I want to direct, why shouldn't I attention away from the way it had been directed down through the year?

01:43:39.000 --> 01:43:48.000
For example, you go through Louisiana and Texas, and you can see those plants and et cetera there,

01:43:48.000 --> 01:43:52.000
that were built by the federal government.

01:43:52.000 --> 01:43:55.000
And I was going to be further farmers.

01:43:55.000 --> 01:44:10.000
I was going to fight for the farmers, but I was not going to go with the mentality that nothing can come to the Delta that will hinder farmers.

01:44:10.000 --> 01:44:16.000
And it should point out that Delta planters have historically had a lot of political power.

01:44:16.000 --> 01:44:23.000
They had political power, the most political two of my friends.

01:44:23.000 --> 01:44:30.000
I got a chance to meet both of them, and campaign on the stump with some of John Stendon's native too.

01:44:30.000 --> 01:44:35.000
And they both was my friend, Jim Eastland, I got to know him, he was my friend.

01:44:35.000 --> 01:44:43.000
I think people, because of what has happened, it's hard for people to realize that when you were running for Congress back then,

01:44:43.000 --> 01:44:49.000
there were a lot of important Democrats elected to office that they supported you.

01:44:49.000 --> 01:44:51.000
Yes, sir.

01:44:51.000 --> 01:44:57.000
And when I ran for office, we did not have the districts that we have now.

01:44:57.000 --> 01:45:11.000
My district ran from down in Port Gibson all the way over to Wefster County, all the way up and over to Wefster County.

01:45:11.000 --> 01:45:24.000
And then even with that district, another thing that we found out when we did a study of the election,

01:45:24.000 --> 01:45:34.000
if we had had poll watches at other places, at say, another places we would have won.

01:45:34.000 --> 01:45:40.000
I've been talking about the racial tactics in that campaign.

01:45:40.000 --> 01:45:44.000
You tell us about your opponents and how he campaigned.

01:45:44.000 --> 01:45:46.000
Web Franklin, who was...

01:45:46.000 --> 01:45:55.000
Well, Wef campaigned, he had a lot of money to campaign.

01:45:55.000 --> 01:46:16.000
I had just enough to get it out, but, you know, way up so far as I'm concerned, I'm the kind of individual that we can have different philosophies and we can disagree and I don't follow with you and get angry with you.

01:46:17.000 --> 01:46:25.000
And, you know, a lot of folks did not turn out in some areas.

01:46:25.000 --> 01:46:38.000
And some areas, well, frankly speaking right here in the Holmes County, down in the Bay of the Civil Rights Movement, I didn't get to turn out down there.

01:46:38.000 --> 01:46:40.000
Was that because of the Eddie Carthane?

01:46:40.000 --> 01:46:41.000
Yes, yes, yes.

01:46:41.000 --> 01:46:47.000
Carthane was a mayor of Chula and he was accused of a number of crimes.

01:46:47.000 --> 01:46:48.000
Yes.

01:46:48.000 --> 01:46:52.000
And how did that play out into the election then?

01:46:52.000 --> 01:47:05.000
Well, it played out into the election that I was not coming down and put my arms around him.

01:47:05.000 --> 01:47:10.000
And essentially saying, you know, let the court system operate.

01:47:10.000 --> 01:47:11.000
Yes, that's right.

01:47:11.000 --> 01:47:12.000
That's right.

01:47:12.000 --> 01:47:14.000
There was some folks who didn't like that.

01:47:14.000 --> 01:47:15.000
That's right.

01:47:15.000 --> 01:47:18.000
Did you think that cost you the election?

01:47:18.000 --> 01:47:22.000
That cost me the election.

01:47:22.000 --> 01:47:32.000
If the Mausdom had turned out the way they have turned out for me every other time I've run, I would have won.

01:47:33.000 --> 01:47:37.000
Got far to 9% plus, that's then get 50% plus.

01:47:37.000 --> 01:47:39.000
Did you think you were going to win?

01:47:39.000 --> 01:47:40.000
Way say.

01:47:40.000 --> 01:47:43.000
Did you think you were going to win an election thing?

01:47:43.000 --> 01:47:46.000
I wasn't sure. I know was.

01:47:46.000 --> 01:47:49.000
I was always, you know, curious. I wasn't sure.

01:47:49.000 --> 01:47:54.000
Well, this is a much interactive national attention.

01:47:54.000 --> 01:48:01.000
You were very charitable with Mr. Franklin, but I just found one of this campaigns of the slogan.

01:48:02.000 --> 01:48:05.000
You left Web Franklin, he's one of us.

01:48:05.000 --> 01:48:07.000
Now what does that mean?

01:48:07.000 --> 01:48:12.000
Well, that's playing, that's racism.

01:48:12.000 --> 01:48:18.000
That's racism playing to the White Pope.

01:48:18.000 --> 01:48:22.000
I think another one is, do you know who I'm running against that was another of us?

01:48:22.000 --> 01:48:26.000
Well, that's another one.

01:48:27.000 --> 01:48:33.000
But like I have, you know, that will fight folks.

01:48:33.000 --> 01:48:35.000
And I work with them.

01:48:35.000 --> 01:48:45.000
All right, when I first ran for attempted to run for Speaker Pro Temporal and Mississippi legislature,

01:48:45.000 --> 01:48:51.000
I did not run because there was some African Americans who was not going to vote for me.

01:48:51.000 --> 01:48:55.000
I didn't want that grand cheer and saying, grand mama, grand data.

01:48:55.000 --> 01:48:58.000
Why you didn't vote for that black man?

01:48:58.000 --> 01:49:04.000
But the second time around, you know, I said, I am going to run.

01:49:04.000 --> 01:49:09.000
I'm begging you for your support and pleading with you for your support.

01:49:09.000 --> 01:49:12.000
If you don't support me, I'm running anyway.

01:49:12.000 --> 01:49:20.000
So out of 35 African Americans, I got 17 of the votes.

01:49:20.000 --> 01:49:29.000
But I got 87% of the total vote of the Mississippi House of Representatives.

01:49:29.000 --> 01:49:38.000
And I got those votes, those men and women, knew that I was black.

01:49:38.000 --> 01:49:40.000
And they saw that I was black.

01:49:40.000 --> 01:49:46.000
But they voted for me as a person, and not as a white person, and not as a black person.

01:49:46.000 --> 01:49:50.000
And you would establish yourself, your credentials, and they respected you.

01:49:50.000 --> 01:49:52.000
That's right.

01:49:52.000 --> 01:50:00.000
And the other time I was chairman of the Speaker Pro Temporal,

01:50:00.000 --> 01:50:05.000
there was times when they tried to get me to spin in the rear.

01:50:05.000 --> 01:50:08.000
So I was, I saw the physical fails of how.

01:50:08.000 --> 01:50:11.000
If you put the money in the budget, we're spinning.

01:50:11.000 --> 01:50:14.000
But if you don't put the money in the budget,

01:50:14.000 --> 01:50:17.000
we will not spin it.

01:50:17.000 --> 01:50:20.000
Just a quick word about your second campaign.

01:50:20.000 --> 01:50:24.000
You came so close in the first campaign for the House.

01:50:24.000 --> 01:50:27.000
Two years later, you ran against Franklin again.

01:50:27.000 --> 01:50:34.000
What was different in that campaign and talked a little bit about how that went down?

01:50:34.000 --> 01:50:38.000
Well, the campaigns went very much the same.

01:50:38.000 --> 01:50:46.000
The second campaign that we were, you know, we were better organized,

01:50:46.000 --> 01:50:50.000
and we knew more about what we were doing.

01:50:50.000 --> 01:50:56.000
But the two campaigns went very much the same.

01:50:56.000 --> 01:51:04.000
There were several other farmers in the Delta that, you know, tried to support me

01:51:04.000 --> 01:51:08.000
and tried to get the rest of the farmers to support me.

01:51:08.000 --> 01:51:16.000
But if the farmers of the Delta had supported me,

01:51:16.000 --> 01:51:21.000
I would have worn particularly the second election.

01:51:21.000 --> 01:51:24.000
I remember that election.

01:51:24.000 --> 01:51:29.000
And some of us were thinking that what was working against you,

01:51:29.000 --> 01:51:35.000
was they identified you as being with the Civil Rights Movement as part of the Civil Rights Movement.

01:51:35.000 --> 01:51:42.000
Yes, and then when you did have a Black candidate eventually winning my guest beat,

01:51:42.000 --> 01:51:45.000
why he was not identified with the Civil Rights Movement.

01:51:45.000 --> 01:51:50.000
Well, one of the things that asked us though, we had changed the district.

01:51:50.000 --> 01:51:55.000
We had changed the district when they asked for ran.

01:51:55.000 --> 01:51:59.000
Much larger Black district.

01:51:59.000 --> 01:52:01.000
Yeah, we had changed the population.

01:52:01.000 --> 01:52:04.000
The percentage of population was larger.

01:52:04.000 --> 01:52:07.000
We had really given him a winnable district.

01:52:07.000 --> 01:52:14.000
You see, I'd really, so far as if you're going to take Mississippi, black and white as it was then,

01:52:14.000 --> 01:52:22.000
with my district running all up into Warnona and Owlin into Wefster County.

01:52:22.000 --> 01:52:27.000
Well, they had Jerry mandered that as soon as it looked like Blacks were going to vote.

01:52:27.000 --> 01:52:31.000
So this would not be an overwhelmingly black district.

01:52:31.000 --> 01:52:33.000
Then they made it an overwhelmingly black district.

01:52:33.000 --> 01:52:37.000
And of course, that made it more difficult for Democrats to win another district.

01:52:37.000 --> 01:52:38.000
That's right.

01:52:38.000 --> 01:52:41.000
This is what we're dealing with now.

01:52:41.000 --> 01:52:48.000
Well, I was going to point out that after that, you came back and you continued to serve with distinction in the legislature.

01:52:48.000 --> 01:52:53.000
In 1992, you elected Speaker Pro-Kam of the House.

01:52:53.000 --> 01:52:59.000
And in 2000, there were 35 black representatives in the Mississippi legislature.

01:52:59.000 --> 01:53:02.000
And that represents some progress at least.

01:53:02.000 --> 01:53:06.000
But before we let you go, one thing we haven't talked about is your family.

01:53:06.000 --> 01:53:10.000
Tell us about your family.

01:53:10.000 --> 01:53:13.000
Well, whether you want Minnesota.

01:53:13.000 --> 01:53:17.000
Well, I mean, you were married in 1971 and you had...

01:53:17.000 --> 01:53:23.000
Yes, I didn't get married until I think I was 38 years old.

01:53:23.000 --> 01:53:34.000
I had real family here, my sister's children, and helped to educate them.

01:53:34.000 --> 01:53:38.000
And they're done well today.

01:53:38.000 --> 01:53:46.000
As I said, my nephew that I've raised here, he is a cardiologist specialist.

01:53:46.000 --> 01:53:49.000
He's a cardiologist in California.

01:53:49.000 --> 01:53:59.000
And he was the youngest cardiologist at the time when he graduated from the University of Michigan.

01:53:59.000 --> 01:54:04.000
And my great-grandpa was slaves here.

01:54:04.000 --> 01:54:06.000
And they bought the place.

01:54:06.000 --> 01:54:09.000
And my grandparent was here.

01:54:09.000 --> 01:54:15.000
And my grandparent, as well as my parent, always taught me that I was somebody.

01:54:15.000 --> 01:54:18.000
And my education was important.

01:54:18.000 --> 01:54:20.000
And you taught your children the same thing?

01:54:20.000 --> 01:54:23.000
And I taught my children the same thing.

01:54:23.000 --> 01:54:30.000
For example, you know, that's my wife's first wife's photo up there.

01:54:30.000 --> 01:54:34.000
Sometimes it'd be two dozen little bars out there.

01:54:34.000 --> 01:54:38.000
They'd be playing with different equipment that they had.

01:54:38.000 --> 01:54:44.000
But I had them to know that you are not anymore.

01:54:44.000 --> 01:54:47.000
And they would be playing in those little boys out there.

01:54:47.000 --> 01:54:51.000
But once they grow up, they go one way.

01:54:51.000 --> 01:54:54.000
And hopefully you're going to go another way.

01:54:54.000 --> 01:54:59.000
But I tell them not, if you go the way I want you to go, I'm going to stick with you.

01:54:59.000 --> 01:55:05.000
But now, if you go the way, you want to go, and they're going to write the right answer.

01:55:05.000 --> 01:55:09.000
You can be sitting on the big, stockpots that ever needs it.

01:55:09.000 --> 01:55:11.000
I weigh that.

01:55:11.000 --> 01:55:15.000
But you go have to get out and take care of your own if you don't.

01:55:15.000 --> 01:55:18.000
And they both did it.

01:55:18.000 --> 01:55:21.000
And they both are lawyers.

01:55:21.000 --> 01:55:25.000
You have been on the scene for a long time.

01:55:25.000 --> 01:55:30.000
The final question that I'm asking most of the people that we are interviewing

01:55:30.000 --> 01:55:37.000
is one of the best and most positive changes that they can place in the state during your lifetime.

01:55:37.000 --> 01:55:45.000
So what pressing problems remain to be solved?

01:55:45.000 --> 01:55:55.000
I'm hesitating, hesitating not because, like a word.

01:55:55.000 --> 01:56:02.000
But the main problem I see in the state of Mississippi right now,

01:56:02.000 --> 01:56:17.000
we need to eradicate political parties because we have government now by the party and by the party and not for the people.

01:56:17.000 --> 01:56:21.000
And you have government now.

01:56:21.000 --> 01:56:29.000
If this party is far, and it's like that in Washington, this one going to be against it and vice versa.

01:56:29.000 --> 01:56:43.000
And our political parties, as I see it, and I have a right to believe in what I believe in because I have been out there.

01:56:43.000 --> 01:56:50.000
Our political parties are the greatest hindrances in the state of Mississippi today.

01:56:50.000 --> 01:56:52.000
It's sort of like there's a Washington.

01:56:52.000 --> 01:56:55.000
There's like it is in Washington.

01:56:55.000 --> 01:57:00.000
But if the Democrats want it, then they're going to make Democrats look good, we ain't no beefy.

01:57:00.000 --> 01:57:04.000
If the Republicans want it, we ain't no beefy.

01:57:04.000 --> 01:57:10.000
What's the biggest positive change in the state in the state?

01:57:10.000 --> 01:57:22.000
Well, the biggest positive change that I've taken place in the state is that, you know, people are free,

01:57:22.000 --> 01:57:33.000
having much change taking place really, since the civil rights movement, people are free to go where they want to go,

01:57:33.000 --> 01:57:39.000
go in the other place they want to eat and go to any motel you want to in the state.

01:57:39.000 --> 01:57:44.000
But the civil rights movement was great.

01:57:44.000 --> 01:57:46.000
It was great.

01:57:46.000 --> 01:57:51.000
We couldn't have been where we are today without the civil rights movement.

01:57:51.000 --> 01:58:11.000
But I'm afraid, and I'm working on it right now, that if we don't do something, history is going to record that for lack of leadership in Mississippi, all of the good works of the civil rights movement die.

01:58:11.000 --> 01:58:14.000
And I'm working on that right now.

01:58:14.000 --> 01:58:22.000
Well, that is probably a good way to end that representative Clark has spent his whole life in public service, and he's not through yet.

01:58:22.000 --> 01:58:26.000
Thank you again for giving it your time.

01:58:26.000 --> 01:58:30.000
This has been a splendid time for us.

01:58:30.000 --> 01:58:33.000
Thank you, thank you, thank you very much.

01:58:33.000 --> 01:58:34.000
Oh, I was.

